WEBVTT

00:00.968 --> 00:02.670
Previously
on "The Good Doctor"...

00:02.703 --> 00:03.537
Ethan: How hard can it be

00:03.571 --> 00:06.440
to just act like
a normal human being?!

00:06.474 --> 00:07.641
[ Grunts ]
No!

00:07.675 --> 00:09.343
Stop petting
that stupid rabbit!

00:09.377 --> 00:11.445
[ Thud ]
We're never
going home again.

00:11.479 --> 00:13.114
We have each other,
and that's all we need.

00:13.147 --> 00:16.517
Shaun: My brother went to heaven
in front of my eyes.

00:18.319 --> 00:20.054
Steve: Never forget,
you're the smart one.

00:20.088 --> 00:22.156
And I'm proud of you,
Shaun.

00:22.190 --> 00:23.257
[ Television playing ]

00:23.291 --> 00:24.725
[ Knocking on door ]

00:24.758 --> 00:26.460
[ Birds chirping ]

00:26.494 --> 00:27.528
[ Knocking continues ]

00:27.561 --> 00:28.796
Kevin: Dad?

00:34.168 --> 00:35.803
Hey!

00:35.836 --> 00:37.205
Hey! [ Laughs ]

00:37.238 --> 00:38.139
I missed you, too!

00:38.172 --> 00:40.274
Oh, Penny, come.

00:40.308 --> 00:42.210
Stay.

00:42.243 --> 00:44.412
Hey, Dad.

00:44.445 --> 00:46.514
Sorry it's so early.
I just landed.

00:46.547 --> 00:48.482
Actually,
you're a bit late.

00:48.516 --> 00:49.683
Five weeks.

00:49.717 --> 00:52.820
I know.
I know.

00:52.853 --> 00:57.091
I'm sorry.
I-I-It's a long story, okay?

00:57.125 --> 00:58.792
But h-how was it?

00:58.826 --> 01:01.195
It was
your mother's funeral.

01:04.365 --> 01:05.733
Dad, I'm --

01:08.402 --> 01:09.403
[ Exhales sharply ]

01:15.443 --> 01:16.610
Okay.

01:16.644 --> 01:18.812
Well, um,
you have my cell number.

01:18.846 --> 01:21.749
It only works
if you answer it.

01:21.782 --> 01:23.417
[ Sighs ]

01:26.687 --> 01:28.789
[ Thumping, glass shattering ]

01:28.822 --> 01:30.391
Dad?

01:30.424 --> 01:31.859
Dad?!

01:31.892 --> 01:33.527
[ Wheezing ]
Dad!

01:33.561 --> 01:35.563
Hey, hey!
Hey -- you okay?

01:35.596 --> 01:37.331
You okay?
You can't breathe?!

01:37.365 --> 01:38.266
No? Okay.

01:38.299 --> 01:41.402
Hold on, I'm gonna call
for help, okay?

01:41.435 --> 01:42.770
911? My dad collapsed!

01:42.803 --> 01:44.472
He can't -- he can't breathe,
please hurry!

01:44.505 --> 01:45.606
Just hold on, Dad!

01:50.544 --> 01:53.214
[ Indistinct P.A. announcement ]

01:53.247 --> 01:54.748
Good morning, everyone!

01:54.782 --> 01:56.617
Right on time.
What, did you sleep here

01:56.650 --> 01:59.453
or use
a teleportation device?

01:59.487 --> 02:01.855
I used
a teleportation device.

02:01.889 --> 02:03.624
[ Laughs ]

02:03.657 --> 02:05.926
Nonsensical questions
usually imply sarcasm,

02:05.959 --> 02:08.662
which I've found people
often answer sarcastically.

02:08.696 --> 02:09.597
Good one.

02:09.630 --> 02:12.566
Trauma wants a consult
on a 66-year-old male

02:12.600 --> 02:14.768
who collapsed
from severe anaphylaxis,

02:14.802 --> 02:16.837
complicated
by respiratory arrest.

02:16.870 --> 02:18.472
His son just got back
from Thailand.

02:18.506 --> 02:20.574
Almost immediately, the father
had his allergic reaction.

02:20.608 --> 02:22.810
Merrill: [ Groaning ]

02:22.843 --> 02:24.412
Patient has
a few allergies --

02:24.445 --> 02:25.746
pollen, mold, shellfish --

02:25.779 --> 02:27.815
but no corresponding allergens
were in evidence.

02:27.848 --> 02:30.351
Why are we doing a
surgical consult on an allergy?

02:30.384 --> 02:31.785
Well, we're not.
We're doing a consult

02:31.819 --> 02:33.954
on the excruciating
abdominal pain he now has.

02:33.987 --> 02:37.258
[ Groaning loudly ]

02:37.291 --> 02:39.660
As you may have heard.

02:39.693 --> 02:43.331
Mr. Wilks, hi,
I'm Dr. Neil Melendez.

02:43.364 --> 02:45.199
Heard you had
some abdominal pain.

02:45.233 --> 02:53.341
**

02:53.374 --> 03:01.549
**

03:01.582 --> 03:09.690
**

03:09.723 --> 03:10.758
-- Captions by VITAC --

03:10.791 --> 03:19.967
**

03:20.000 --> 03:21.635
The guy
was in some serious pain --

03:21.669 --> 03:23.304
10 milligrams
of morphine worth.

03:23.337 --> 03:24.905
Test results show
elevated lipase,

03:24.938 --> 03:26.840
amylase,
pancreatic enzymes.

03:26.874 --> 03:27.841
Pancreas is enlarged.

03:27.875 --> 03:30.544
Could be pancreatitis,
maybe alcohol-induced.

03:30.578 --> 03:31.945
The son said he smelled alcohol
on his father

03:31.979 --> 03:32.913
at 6:00 in the morning.

03:32.946 --> 03:35.249
And anaphylaxis has been known
to precipitate

03:35.283 --> 03:36.917
attacks of pancreatitis.

03:36.950 --> 03:38.486
Guess that's it, then.

03:40.554 --> 03:42.490
Meaning
you totally disagree.

03:42.523 --> 03:44.325
Not everyone who starts
their day off with a Mimosa

03:44.358 --> 03:46.494
fries their pancreas.

03:46.527 --> 03:47.861
Your eyesight must a
hell of a lot better than mine.

03:47.895 --> 03:49.863
Because I can't see
the entire pancreas

03:49.897 --> 03:51.799
due to the overlying
bowel gas.

03:54.435 --> 03:56.804
We'll order an abdominal CT
and take a better look.

03:56.837 --> 03:58.439
There you go.

03:58.472 --> 03:59.907
Where the hell is Murphy?

03:59.940 --> 04:01.542
It's a severe fracture,

04:01.575 --> 04:03.311
but I don't think
you'll need pins.

04:03.344 --> 04:05.012
Young bones tend to heal
very well.

04:05.045 --> 04:08.882
Young Bones? Isn't that
a "Star Trek: Origins"
graphic novel?

04:11.585 --> 04:14.021
I'm not sure.

04:14.054 --> 04:15.556
No, that was a joke.

04:15.589 --> 04:16.857
Where are your parents?

04:16.890 --> 04:18.726
They're coming.
They both work in the city,

04:18.759 --> 04:20.561
so it's a long drive
for them.

04:20.594 --> 04:22.463
I was on
a school field trip,

04:22.496 --> 04:23.864
and I tripped
over my own feet.

04:23.897 --> 04:26.700
Of course, it was
right in front of Shelby Lomar.

04:26.734 --> 04:28.001
At least
it was pretty gross,

04:28.035 --> 04:30.438
so I got some sympathy points
for that.

04:33.541 --> 04:34.975
I would expect this
to have been caused

04:35.008 --> 04:36.777
by a more serious
accident.

04:36.810 --> 04:37.911
Nope, just a trip.

04:37.945 --> 04:39.046
I do that a lot.

04:39.079 --> 04:40.047
What can I say?

04:40.080 --> 04:41.649
I'm clumsy.

04:41.682 --> 04:43.684
Yes. Now follow my finger.

04:43.717 --> 04:50.057
**

04:50.090 --> 04:51.559
You have
some nystagmus --

04:51.592 --> 04:53.661
an involuntary eye movement.

04:53.694 --> 04:55.763
So what's that mean?

04:55.796 --> 04:57.698
When you fell,
did you hit your head?

04:57.731 --> 04:58.799
No.

04:58.832 --> 05:00.000
What, you think I have
brain damage?

05:00.033 --> 05:02.903
Nystagmus can be a sign
of a neurological issue.

05:02.936 --> 05:03.737
Oh.

05:03.771 --> 05:05.072
Well, that would explain
the "C" I got

05:05.105 --> 05:07.908
in social studies.

05:07.941 --> 05:10.344
That was another joke,
wasn't it?

05:10.378 --> 05:12.446
Mm.

05:12.480 --> 05:14.715
I'm going to order
a head CT for you.

05:14.748 --> 05:16.083
Go for it.

05:18.952 --> 05:20.621
Shaun,
are you getting any sleep?

05:20.654 --> 05:21.989
Yes.
Really?

05:22.022 --> 05:23.591
I mean,
really getting sleep?

05:23.624 --> 05:24.858
I got here on time.

05:24.892 --> 05:25.859
Well, that's good.

05:25.893 --> 05:28.128
I used
a teleportation device.

05:28.161 --> 05:32.733
**

05:32.766 --> 05:34.935
Radiology form, please.

05:34.968 --> 05:40.040
**

05:40.073 --> 05:41.742
Shaun, that boy,
he looks like --

05:41.775 --> 05:42.910
Steve.

05:42.943 --> 05:44.412
He does.

05:44.445 --> 05:45.879
Is he related?

05:45.913 --> 05:48.782
His name is Evan Gallico,
so I don't think so.

05:51.084 --> 05:52.753
Wow. That is uncanny.

05:52.786 --> 05:54.087
Just coincidental.

05:54.121 --> 05:56.457
He looks
exactly like your brother.

05:56.490 --> 05:57.491
No, he doesn't.

05:57.525 --> 05:59.393
His hair is shorter.

05:59.427 --> 06:01.094
It freaks me out.
It doesn't freak you out?

06:01.128 --> 06:02.730
No.

06:02.763 --> 06:03.531
It's okay if it does --

06:03.564 --> 06:05.833
No, he's not Steve.
Steve's dead.

06:10.203 --> 06:12.806
"I used a teleportation device"
was a joke.

06:14.742 --> 06:16.877
Yeah,
that's...that's good.

06:19.780 --> 06:22.950
[ Indistinct P.A. announcement ]

06:25.653 --> 06:28.055
Kevin: So, I couldn't come
to Mom's funeral

06:28.088 --> 06:30.491
because I fell in love.

06:32.560 --> 06:34.094
She was another teacher
at the school.

06:34.127 --> 06:36.430
A Thai woman.

06:36.464 --> 06:37.731
And she was kind
and --

06:37.765 --> 06:42.069
and beautiful
and loving...

06:42.102 --> 06:45.005
and very, very sick.

06:45.038 --> 06:47.675
She had
a congenital heart defect.

06:53.113 --> 06:57.050
Look, if you don't want
to tell me where you've been

06:57.084 --> 06:58.686
for the last six months,
then don't.

06:58.719 --> 06:59.753
It's your business.

06:59.787 --> 07:01.622
But don't insult
my intelligence.

07:01.655 --> 07:02.990
Well, I couldn't
just leave her.

07:03.023 --> 07:04.525
You couldn't leave her
for five minutes

07:04.558 --> 07:05.559
to make a phone call?

07:05.593 --> 07:07.561
[ Knocking on door ]

07:07.595 --> 07:09.129
This a bad time?

07:09.162 --> 07:12.700
No, come in.

07:16.937 --> 07:18.071
According to the CT,

07:18.105 --> 07:19.573
you have a lesion
on your pancreas.

07:19.607 --> 07:21.041
Well, what do you think
this lesion could be?

07:21.074 --> 07:21.809
Not sure.

07:21.842 --> 07:23.877
That's why we need
to biopsy it.

07:23.911 --> 07:25.913
It could
just be a benign cyst.

07:25.946 --> 07:26.814
Or...?

07:26.847 --> 07:29.216
Or...

07:29.249 --> 07:32.252
it could be cancer,
right?

07:32.285 --> 07:33.954
We'll know soon enough.

07:33.987 --> 07:42.696
**

07:42.730 --> 07:50.871
**

07:50.904 --> 07:52.506
This won't take long.

07:52.540 --> 07:54.241
Evan: I know.
I've had two of these.

07:54.274 --> 07:55.976
One more
and I get my Scout badge.

07:56.009 --> 07:57.878
[ Chuckles ]

08:00.548 --> 08:01.615
That was funny.

08:01.649 --> 08:03.250
Tough to tell
without looking at you,

08:03.283 --> 08:05.753
but I'm guessing
that was sarcasm.

08:05.786 --> 08:07.788
No. I have autism,

08:07.821 --> 08:11.024
which makes it hard
for me to read social cues.

08:11.058 --> 08:12.192
Jokes are difficult.

08:12.225 --> 08:14.895
I used to know a kid
with autism. Peter.

08:14.928 --> 08:18.799
He was kind of weird
but super nice.

08:18.832 --> 08:20.267
Used to know?

08:20.300 --> 08:22.135
You don't know him
anymore?

08:22.169 --> 08:23.737
He died.

08:23.771 --> 08:25.973
Hit by a car.

08:26.006 --> 08:28.642
You know anyone
who died?

08:28.676 --> 08:30.177
My brother.

08:30.210 --> 08:31.545
That sucks.

08:34.982 --> 08:37.050
Why did you have
the other CT scans?

08:37.084 --> 08:39.319
My parents have...

08:39.352 --> 08:41.589
uh, what's the word
for fear of getting sick?

08:41.622 --> 08:43.190
Hypochondriasis?

08:43.223 --> 08:45.125
Mm, no, worse than that.

08:45.158 --> 08:47.895
They have...nosophobia.

08:47.928 --> 08:49.797
I love that word.

08:49.830 --> 08:52.733
What do you think
of Miss Gannett?

08:52.766 --> 08:53.867
She's nice.

08:53.901 --> 08:56.870
I think
she's callipygian.

08:56.904 --> 08:58.271
She's what?

08:58.305 --> 08:59.673
Callipygian?

08:59.707 --> 09:02.643
It means "having
shapely buttocks," Shaun.

09:02.676 --> 09:03.777
Duh.

09:06.246 --> 09:07.948
You read the dictionary.

09:07.981 --> 09:10.951
What it lacks in plot,
it makes up for in vocab.

09:10.984 --> 09:13.721
So, you married?

09:13.754 --> 09:15.956
Girlfriend?

09:15.989 --> 09:17.691
Boyfriend?

09:17.725 --> 09:19.059
Tropical fish?

09:21.261 --> 09:22.830
I like Lea.

09:22.863 --> 09:24.965
Ooh. And who's Lea?

09:24.998 --> 09:26.166
Lea is a friend.

09:26.199 --> 09:28.168
A friend you date?

09:28.201 --> 09:30.237
A friend with benefits?

09:30.270 --> 09:32.973
I lend her batteries
sometimes.

09:33.006 --> 09:34.007
I like
where this is going...

09:34.041 --> 09:35.308
[ Machine beeps ]

09:38.411 --> 09:41.081
So, you know,
keep going.

09:41.114 --> 09:43.350
'Cause if you don't,
I will.

09:43.383 --> 09:45.052
It's kind of my thing,
you know?

09:45.085 --> 09:47.220
Just constant talking --
annoys everyone.

09:47.254 --> 09:49.657
Murphy.
Well,
I guess not everyone.

09:49.690 --> 09:51.792
Hey.
My family's pretty
used to me now. I mean...

09:51.825 --> 09:52.826
Hey.
[ Button clicks, beeps ]

09:52.860 --> 09:55.763
...my friends are
very talkative as well, so...

09:55.796 --> 09:57.297
You're giving
the fractured arm a head CT?

09:57.330 --> 09:58.799
Yes.
Get back
to the pancreas.

09:58.832 --> 09:59.733
He's not clumsy.

09:59.767 --> 10:02.602
He has a brain tumor
behind the inner ear.

10:04.838 --> 10:06.273
Forget the pancreas.

10:13.246 --> 10:15.248
Mr. and Mrs. Gallico?

10:15.282 --> 10:16.784
Hi.
Hi.

10:16.817 --> 10:18.018
I'm Dr. Shaun Murphy.

10:18.051 --> 10:19.152
I'm treating your son.

10:19.186 --> 10:20.220
Well, how is he?

10:20.253 --> 10:21.689
We were told
it was a bad break,

10:21.722 --> 10:23.256
but it should heal
no problem.

10:23.290 --> 10:24.958
I know why Evan tripped.

10:24.992 --> 10:27.795
He had a tumor
in the temporal bone
behind his left ear,

10:27.828 --> 10:29.329
which is affecting
his balance.

10:29.362 --> 10:32.065
I've arranged for a consult
with Dr. Najid in oncology

10:32.099 --> 10:33.667
and she's going --
No, that won't be necessary.

10:33.701 --> 10:35.135
We --

10:35.168 --> 10:37.204
We already have
an oncologist.

10:37.237 --> 10:39.072
[ Sighs ]

10:39.106 --> 10:42.442
Evan's been diagnosed
with stage four osteosarcoma.

10:42.475 --> 10:44.444
He was complaining
of a sore shin.

10:44.477 --> 10:48.315
The last thing that we expected
was bone cancer.

10:48.348 --> 10:49.683
The doctors at SFM,

10:49.717 --> 10:52.152
they gave him
a year to live.

10:55.188 --> 10:57.958
That was seven months ago.

10:57.991 --> 11:01.261
Osteosarcoma explains
the severity of his fracture --

11:01.294 --> 11:03.831
he will need pins in his arm
after all.

11:03.864 --> 11:05.098
Uh, can we see him?

11:05.132 --> 11:07.400
Yes. He's in room 414.

11:07.434 --> 11:09.269
Uh, Dr. Murphy?

11:11.772 --> 11:15.108
He doesn't know
about his diagnosis.

11:15.142 --> 11:18.846
We would really like
to keep it that way.

11:18.879 --> 11:22.315
**

11:28.889 --> 11:29.823
He's the patient.

11:29.857 --> 11:31.859
Doesn't he have the right
to know the truth?

11:31.892 --> 11:32.760
Well, no.

11:32.793 --> 11:35.128
He's also a minor,
so, no, he doesn't.

11:35.162 --> 11:36.396
Evan's
very intelligent --

11:36.429 --> 11:37.364
he'd be able
to handle it.

11:37.397 --> 11:40.067
Well, Shaun,
maybe it's not just about Evan.

11:40.100 --> 11:43.003
Maybe it's about his parents,
as well.

11:43.036 --> 11:46.907
Maybe it's just too difficult
for them to tell Evan right now.

11:46.940 --> 11:47.841
I don't know.

11:47.875 --> 11:49.242
Then they're the ones
who shouldn't be told.

11:49.276 --> 11:50.911
Well, let me ask you this,
Shaun --

11:50.944 --> 11:53.947
what's so wrong
about Evan being allowed

11:53.981 --> 11:56.516
to enjoy as much of his life
as possible?

11:56.549 --> 11:58.318
Evan wants to know
the truth.

11:58.351 --> 11:59.486
How do you know that?

12:03.824 --> 12:07.260
If this were Steve,
if this were your brother,

12:07.294 --> 12:08.495
would he want to know
the truth?

12:08.528 --> 12:10.030
Is that what this is?

12:15.102 --> 12:17.370
Dad's such a tool.

12:17.404 --> 12:18.405
I found
my birthday present --

12:18.438 --> 12:20.373
in their closet,
right where they always hide it.

12:20.407 --> 12:21.341
I was just about
to open it

12:21.374 --> 12:23.543
when Dad caught me snooping
and freaked out.

12:23.576 --> 12:26.914
I hate
all that phony surprise stuff.

12:26.947 --> 12:29.917
It's an
AquaBlast Water Cannon.

12:29.950 --> 12:32.152
I was with Mom
when she bought it.

12:32.185 --> 12:33.420
Thank you, Shaun.

12:33.453 --> 12:35.422
Your honesty's refreshing!

12:38.959 --> 12:42.229
Yes, he would want to know
the truth.

12:42.262 --> 12:44.898
Well, there's nothing
we can do about it.

12:44.932 --> 12:46.900
It's not your decision --
it's theirs.

12:46.934 --> 12:48.301
He's their son.

12:50.070 --> 12:55.508
**

12:55.542 --> 12:56.343
[ Door beeps ]

12:56.376 --> 12:57.911
[ Sighs ]

12:57.945 --> 13:03.516
**

13:03.550 --> 13:04.885
Claire, I need you.

13:06.854 --> 13:08.321
Sure, what's up?

13:10.057 --> 13:12.225
I need someone
to lie for me.

13:12.259 --> 13:15.195
Okay...

13:15.228 --> 13:17.030
I'm flattered?

13:20.533 --> 13:23.403
Hey, doc?

13:23.436 --> 13:26.073
There's something
I need to tell my dad.

13:26.106 --> 13:29.109
We haven't moved him.
He's still in room, uh, 326.

13:31.979 --> 13:35.248
Do you have
a medical question for me?

13:35.282 --> 13:36.616
Is he dying?

13:36.649 --> 13:38.085
We don't know yet.

13:38.118 --> 13:40.087
The biopsy
will tell us more.

13:40.120 --> 13:41.221
Okay.

13:45.558 --> 13:47.394
My dad is a good guy.

13:49.662 --> 13:53.901
We've just never been
on the same page, you know?

13:53.934 --> 13:57.337
My mother was the one
that I could talk to --

13:57.370 --> 14:00.073
same for him.

14:00.107 --> 14:04.144
So, without her,

14:04.177 --> 14:06.379
we're both pretty useless.

14:12.319 --> 14:14.521
Room 326.

14:14.554 --> 14:15.355
Right.

14:15.388 --> 14:22.562
**

14:22.595 --> 14:24.631
Dr. Murphy called me in
for a second opinion.

14:24.664 --> 14:29.169
Um, you need some pins
in your arm.

14:29.202 --> 14:30.137
Why?

14:30.170 --> 14:31.571
What's changed?

14:31.604 --> 14:33.941
Well, after studying
the radiology report,

14:33.974 --> 14:35.408
given how bad
the break is,

14:35.442 --> 14:37.410
we just think it would be
a prudent step

14:37.444 --> 14:40.613
to ensure an efficient and
thorough mending to the break.

14:40.647 --> 14:42.950
Will I be able
to play baseball again?

14:42.983 --> 14:44.351
Well, I don't see why not,

14:44.384 --> 14:45.618
once it's completely healed,

14:45.652 --> 14:47.320
after some physiotherapy.

14:47.354 --> 14:49.089
How long
before I can pitch?

14:49.122 --> 14:50.958
It's hard to say.

14:50.991 --> 14:53.026
[ Monitor beeping ]

14:56.997 --> 14:58.999
He wanted someone to lie
for him.

14:59.032 --> 15:03.436
[ Scoffs ]
And he picked you.

15:03.470 --> 15:05.405
Merrill's son asked
for personal advice.

15:05.438 --> 15:06.539
And he picked you.

15:06.573 --> 15:08.275
I know, right?
[ Scoffs ]

15:08.308 --> 15:11.644
He's lying to his dad
about something.

15:11.678 --> 15:13.246
Yeah? What?

15:13.280 --> 15:14.614
I don't know.

15:14.647 --> 15:16.183
You didn't ask?

15:16.216 --> 15:19.686
It didn't seem relevant,
medically.

15:19.719 --> 15:22.589
You know it's not that difficult
to be a human being.

15:22.622 --> 15:25.058
Just tell him
to "come clean,"

15:25.092 --> 15:27.394
"honesty
is the best policy,"

15:27.427 --> 15:30.030
"a lie is a stone
in your heart."

15:30.063 --> 15:31.364
Who said the last one?

15:31.398 --> 15:32.665
Me.

15:32.699 --> 15:33.700
I made it up.

15:33.733 --> 15:34.634
Hmm.

15:34.667 --> 15:37.370
[ Chuckles ]

15:37.404 --> 15:40.007
And...I got it.

15:42.309 --> 15:43.376
[ Beeping quickens ]
He's anaphylactic.

15:43.410 --> 15:44.311
Would you get me an epi?
I'm coming out.

15:44.344 --> 15:46.379
The throat's constricting.
Pull the tube.

15:46.413 --> 15:49.149
[ Gasping ]

15:49.182 --> 15:51.318
[ Saw whirring ]

15:54.721 --> 15:56.289
[ Whirring stops ]

15:59.526 --> 16:03.563
So, what's up
with "Dr. Browne"?

16:03.596 --> 16:07.200
She's Lea, isn't she?

16:07.234 --> 16:08.235
Claire is my colleague.

16:08.268 --> 16:12.639
Oh, come on, I saw the way
you were looking at her.

16:12.672 --> 16:13.740
How?

16:16.143 --> 16:17.777
I don't think
I look like that.

16:17.810 --> 16:21.114
Okay, so then why'd you
call her in for a "consult"?

16:21.148 --> 16:23.483
Mm...

16:23.516 --> 16:25.618
Okay.

16:25.652 --> 16:29.256
Yes, she's better at talking
to people than I am.

16:29.289 --> 16:32.759
Wow. I counted
like 50 tells there.

16:32.792 --> 16:35.262
You really suck
at lying.
I know.

16:35.295 --> 16:37.497
Too bad.
It's an important social skill.

16:39.632 --> 16:42.469
So how do you know
when to lie?

16:42.502 --> 16:44.137
When people
need to know things,

16:44.171 --> 16:45.105
they need to know.

16:45.138 --> 16:46.506
If they don't,

16:46.539 --> 16:48.375
lie through your teeth
and feel good about it.

16:48.408 --> 16:49.776
What if they need
to know the truth,

16:49.809 --> 16:51.278
but it'll hurt them?

16:54.714 --> 16:58.051
Some can handle it,
some can't.

16:58.085 --> 17:00.387
So how do you know
who can and who can't?

17:00.420 --> 17:01.554
You tell the truth.

17:01.588 --> 17:04.224
If they like you after,
then you'll know.

17:04.257 --> 17:05.458
If they don't?

17:05.492 --> 17:08.161
Then it doesn't really matter
anyway.

17:13.200 --> 17:14.467
You have cancer.

17:16.136 --> 17:19.206
[ Sighs ]

17:19.239 --> 17:22.375
Yeah, I know.

17:30.717 --> 17:32.719
My parents took me in
for a sore leg.

17:32.752 --> 17:34.221
After a whole bunch
of tests,

17:34.254 --> 17:35.355
they talked
to the doctor,

17:35.388 --> 17:37.557
then came out
and told me I was fine.

17:37.590 --> 17:40.660
That's it.
Just "fine."

17:40.693 --> 17:44.331
The next day,
they bought me a PS4.

17:44.364 --> 17:46.566
So I Googled my symptoms,

17:46.599 --> 17:48.835
and I narrowed it down
to osteosarcoma

17:48.868 --> 17:50.537
or growing pains.

17:50.570 --> 17:53.640
Kids don't get gaming systems
for growing pains.

17:55.542 --> 17:59.312
Hey, it's okay.

18:01.681 --> 18:03.250
I'm not afraid to die.

18:03.283 --> 18:04.684
You're not?

18:04.717 --> 18:06.686
Well, I mean,
the dying part will suck

18:06.719 --> 18:10.423
if it hurts, but...

18:10.457 --> 18:12.659
I'm not afraid
about the actual death part.

18:12.692 --> 18:15.362
Because you believe
you're going to Heaven?

18:15.395 --> 18:16.829
Because I don't.

18:19.632 --> 18:21.201
If I believe in Heaven,

18:21.234 --> 18:22.602
then I got to believe
in God,

18:22.635 --> 18:25.172
then I got to believe
God made me sick.

18:25.205 --> 18:27.540
How messed up is that?

18:27.574 --> 18:31.278
It's just easier to think
that it's all random

18:31.311 --> 18:33.346
and when it's over,

18:33.380 --> 18:38.185
it's just...

18:38.218 --> 18:39.352
over.

18:44.457 --> 18:46.626
So what about Lea?

18:46.659 --> 18:48.761
Where'd you guys meet?

18:48.795 --> 18:50.430
In the hallway.

18:54.567 --> 18:55.768
That's a beautiful story.

18:55.802 --> 18:57.204
Yes.

18:57.237 --> 18:58.805
She's my neighbor.

18:58.838 --> 19:01.608
Convenient.

19:01.641 --> 19:03.343
He had
another allergic reaction.

19:03.376 --> 19:05.812
The pancreas?
Merrill Wilks, yeah.

19:05.845 --> 19:08.415
And the second attack
was even more severe
than the first.

19:08.448 --> 19:10.517
It coincided with biopsying
the pancreatic lesion,

19:10.550 --> 19:11.851
which now appears
was a cyst.

19:11.884 --> 19:12.852
Well, now we know
he's allergic

19:12.885 --> 19:14.187
to whatever's
in that cyst.

19:14.221 --> 19:15.688
We also that
the next cyst that pops

19:15.722 --> 19:17.757
will probably kill him.
Well, if there is a next.

19:17.790 --> 19:18.691
Let's run a couple tests,

19:18.725 --> 19:20.493
see if there's any evidence
of parasites.

19:20.527 --> 19:21.761
And MRI his entire body --

19:21.794 --> 19:23.230
if we're lucky,
he only had the two cysts

19:23.263 --> 19:24.364
and he can go home.

19:28.368 --> 19:30.237
Are you looking
for loopholes?

19:30.270 --> 19:31.604
Hoping to save Evan?

19:31.638 --> 19:33.740
Everyone makes mistakes.

19:33.773 --> 19:34.941
Which means you should
double-check

19:34.974 --> 19:36.643
every file
in the hospital.

19:36.676 --> 19:40.680
The oncologist flagged
his neutrophil count of 634

19:40.713 --> 19:41.781
as low.

19:41.814 --> 19:42.715
That is low.

19:42.749 --> 19:43.616
Low normal.

19:43.650 --> 19:46.386
I can still hear
the word "low" in there.

19:46.419 --> 19:47.787
Mm.

19:50.957 --> 19:52.859
He's just a kid.

19:52.892 --> 19:55.962
I know how hard it is
to think of him dying.

19:55.995 --> 19:58.465
He's okay with that.

19:58.498 --> 19:59.966
I find that
hard to believe.

19:59.999 --> 20:01.334
We all die --

20:01.368 --> 20:03.536
if we accepted that,
we'd be happier.

20:03.570 --> 20:07.974
Maybe. But we're not good
with contentment.

20:08.007 --> 20:10.477
Fighting death
is what keeps us alive.

20:10.510 --> 20:11.711
[ Computer beeps ]

20:11.744 --> 20:17.317
**

20:17.350 --> 20:18.818
Okay.

20:20.052 --> 20:21.788
We got a hit --
Echinococcus.

20:21.821 --> 20:23.556
Jared: Echinococcus?

20:23.590 --> 20:24.691
The cysts are filled
with tapeworms?

20:24.724 --> 20:26.326
Cysts?
There are more?

20:26.359 --> 20:27.894
Three more?
Four more.

20:27.927 --> 20:29.362
You missed the one
in his brain.

20:29.396 --> 20:32.565
**

20:32.599 --> 20:34.434
[ Knocking on door ]
Jared: Dr. Glassman?

20:34.467 --> 20:35.635
Yeah?

20:35.668 --> 20:37.337
You used to be a neurosurgeon,
right?

20:37.370 --> 20:38.671
So they say.

20:38.705 --> 20:39.939
Take this, will you?

20:41.974 --> 20:43.276
I need one.

20:43.310 --> 20:44.477
Who would you recommend?

20:44.511 --> 20:45.878
What you got?

20:51.784 --> 20:53.453
Wow, that's cool.

20:56.022 --> 20:58.458
How the hell did I get tapeworms
in my head?

20:58.491 --> 21:00.460
No idea, but you do.

21:00.493 --> 21:02.662
You can pick up the eggs
from coyotes or wolves.

21:02.695 --> 21:04.697
You been hanging around
coyotes or wolves?

21:04.731 --> 21:05.932
I live
in the suburbs --

21:05.965 --> 21:07.467
we don't even have
a petting zoo.

21:07.500 --> 21:09.902
You might've had these cysts
for quite some time.

21:09.936 --> 21:11.338
When one of them burst,

21:11.371 --> 21:13.473
that's what caused
the first allergic reaction.

21:13.506 --> 21:15.442
Well, why did it burst?

21:15.475 --> 21:16.876
Why did it burst?

21:16.909 --> 21:20.480
Any sudden movements, twists,
turns, squeeze.

21:20.513 --> 21:21.514
A hug?

21:21.548 --> 21:24.451
Could be.

21:24.484 --> 21:26.553
But you weren't there
for the second one.

21:28.688 --> 21:31.023
I punctured the cyst
on your pancreas

21:31.057 --> 21:32.559
during the biopsy.

21:32.592 --> 21:35.328
As you've seen,
allergic reactions get worse

21:35.362 --> 21:36.162
each time they happen.

21:36.195 --> 21:37.564
So a third one,
that would be bad.

21:37.597 --> 21:38.965
That would be...
[ Chuckles ]

21:38.998 --> 21:39.866
That would be very bad.

21:39.899 --> 21:42.034
So we're gonna have
to surgically remove

21:42.068 --> 21:44.371
all the cysts intact.

21:44.404 --> 21:46.573
Dr. Glassman's
one of the most highly acclaimed

21:46.606 --> 21:47.607
neurosurgeons
in the state.

21:47.640 --> 21:48.808
You are very lucky
to have him.

21:48.841 --> 21:52.945
And Dr. Kalu is fast becoming
a very accomplished flatterer.

21:52.979 --> 21:56.048
The cranial cyst,
that is a big deal.

21:56.082 --> 21:58.651
We're gonna have to take off
the top of your skull.

21:58.685 --> 22:00.720
You'd be digging in
to my brain?

22:00.753 --> 22:02.088
Well, yeah, pretty much.

22:02.121 --> 22:02.955
With saline.

22:02.989 --> 22:04.957
We use it to gently displace
the cyst,

22:04.991 --> 22:07.360
and then, poof,
it magically pops out.

22:07.394 --> 22:08.561
Kind of like
delivering a baby.

22:08.595 --> 22:11.063
You know,
if childbirth were painless.

22:11.097 --> 22:14.467
And then we move on
to the other cysts.

22:14.501 --> 22:16.669
Hey, we're gonna take
good care of you.

22:16.703 --> 22:25.945
**

22:25.978 --> 22:35.455
**

22:35.488 --> 22:44.697
**

22:44.731 --> 22:53.973
**

22:54.006 --> 23:03.516
**

23:03.550 --> 23:12.792
**

23:12.825 --> 23:21.868
**

23:21.901 --> 23:23.970
Evan doesn't have cancer.

23:30.577 --> 23:31.478
* Cowards cowering in concrete
showers in Rikers Island *

23:31.511 --> 23:32.479
* Victims, we the wolves
that's wilding *

23:32.512 --> 23:33.245
* We often smilin'
at sights of violence *

23:33.279 --> 23:34.280
* Acting brave and courageous

23:34.313 --> 23:36.749
* Ain't advantageous
for health and safety *

23:36.783 --> 23:38.117
* So when we say
"run the jewels" *

23:38.150 --> 23:39.819
It might not be cancer!

23:39.852 --> 23:41.588
* And that goes
for a guy or lady *

23:41.621 --> 23:43.590
It might not be cancer!

23:43.623 --> 23:45.692
[ Music stops ]

23:45.725 --> 23:47.460
Look at you on time --
two for two.

23:47.494 --> 23:48.995
It might not be cancer.

23:49.028 --> 23:51.097
Fractured arm?
Yes.

23:51.130 --> 23:53.633
You said he'd been diagnosed
with stage four osteosarcoma.

23:53.666 --> 23:56.469
Evan was diagnosed with the flu
eight months ago,

23:56.503 --> 23:57.937
but his symptoms were actually
a better fit

23:57.970 --> 23:59.005
with Epstein-Barr virus,

23:59.038 --> 24:01.173
which is linked to
Langerhans cell histiocytosis,

24:01.207 --> 24:02.809
which causes
osteolytic lesions

24:02.842 --> 24:04.176
in the long bones
of the upper limbs.

24:04.210 --> 24:05.978
And those lesions
could be misdiagnosed

24:06.012 --> 24:07.146
as signs
of osteosarcoma.

24:07.179 --> 24:08.781
Yes.
What about
his brain tumor?

24:08.815 --> 24:12.519
Langerhans can also manifest
in the skull.

24:12.552 --> 24:13.853
Instead of
a death sentence,

24:13.886 --> 24:15.054
he could have something
that could easily

24:15.087 --> 24:16.022
be treated
with prednisone?

24:16.055 --> 24:18.591
Next, we need to do
a bone-marrow aspiration

24:18.625 --> 24:19.692
to confirm.

24:19.726 --> 24:20.960
I assume
you've looked at his file.

24:20.993 --> 24:22.061
For a very long time.

24:22.094 --> 24:23.496
Well, there must've been
a biopsy.

24:23.530 --> 24:24.697
What did
the pathology report say?

24:24.731 --> 24:25.998
Yes.
There were two biopsies.

24:26.032 --> 24:29.702
Both were positive
for osteosarcoma.

24:29.736 --> 24:32.672
Murphy...
They could be
false positives.

24:32.705 --> 24:34.040
Do you have any idea
how unlikely it is

24:34.073 --> 24:35.107
to have
two false positives?

24:35.141 --> 24:36.142
0.3%.

24:36.175 --> 24:37.977
Which we can comfortably
round off to "not likely."

24:38.010 --> 24:39.512
It is possible --

24:39.546 --> 24:41.648
Yes, but it means telling
the parents of a dying child

24:41.681 --> 24:45.051
that there's hope,
when really there isn't.

24:45.084 --> 24:46.819
Grab a shower
and get ready for rounds.

24:53.626 --> 24:55.094
Glassman:
Wow. [ Chuckles ]

24:55.127 --> 24:56.596
Imaginative and creative.

24:56.629 --> 24:57.363
Yes.

24:57.396 --> 24:58.765
What are the chances
you're right?

24:58.798 --> 24:59.866
0.3%.

24:59.899 --> 25:01.067
330 to 1.

25:01.100 --> 25:03.770
333 to 1.

25:03.803 --> 25:05.304
You really think
that it's worth

25:05.337 --> 25:07.006
putting Evan's parents
through all this?

25:07.039 --> 25:08.174
Of course.

25:08.207 --> 25:10.610
If we did this
333 times,

25:10.643 --> 25:12.912
we'd be giving false hope
to 332 people

25:12.945 --> 25:14.280
for approximately
four hours,

25:14.313 --> 25:15.715
and we'd save one life.

25:15.748 --> 25:18.150
Isn't that worth it?
[ Exhales sharply ]

25:18.184 --> 25:19.786
Anyway, Dr. Melendez
won't let me

25:19.819 --> 25:21.220
ask for consent to test.

25:21.253 --> 25:24.123
What if I don't tell them
what I'm doing?

25:24.156 --> 25:26.325
A blatant ethics violation --
that's your solution?

25:26.358 --> 25:27.627
Yes.

25:27.660 --> 25:29.161
How do I do that?

25:31.363 --> 25:33.966
[ Scoffs ]

25:34.000 --> 25:36.002
Well, uh, [chuckles],

25:36.035 --> 25:38.705
you do it
and then don't tell anyone.

25:38.738 --> 25:40.106
No one.
If anyone asks...

25:40.139 --> 25:42.709
your attending noticed
a low RBC count

25:42.742 --> 25:43.843
and needed to find
the cause --

25:43.876 --> 25:47.580
that's it --
no biggie.

25:47.614 --> 25:48.080
Hmm.

25:48.114 --> 25:54.120
**

25:54.153 --> 25:55.888
[ Coughs ]

25:57.957 --> 26:01.127
You know Wilks' Grocery
on Santa Clara 17th?

26:01.160 --> 26:04.296
It's been an institution
for nearly 60 years.

26:04.330 --> 26:07.366
My grandparents
started it in 1958,

26:07.399 --> 26:10.069
and my wife and I took it over
in '82.

26:10.102 --> 26:11.203
But when my wife got sick

26:11.237 --> 26:13.706
and I started talking to Kevin
about taking it over,

26:13.740 --> 26:16.242
he just...took off.

26:18.077 --> 26:19.345
To him,
it was just a place

26:19.378 --> 26:21.648
to sell lettuce
and toilet paper.

26:24.784 --> 26:29.656
My father chairs a real-estate
development company in the U.K.

26:29.689 --> 26:30.890
Thought I'd be
the perfect person

26:30.923 --> 26:32.625
to set up
the U.S. office.

26:32.659 --> 26:34.994
You wanted to be in
the "helping profession," hmm?

26:35.027 --> 26:37.764
I wanted to be
in my profession.

26:37.797 --> 26:40.199
It's not about how small
or how big the venture is,

26:40.232 --> 26:42.134
it's about doing something
that's yours.

26:45.204 --> 26:46.706
I guess.

26:52.979 --> 26:55.848
When he was little,
we were inseparable.

26:55.882 --> 26:58.317
[ Chuckles ]

26:58.350 --> 27:03.022
Ah, he used to love
to come to the store to "work."

27:03.055 --> 27:06.058
[ Laughs ]

27:06.092 --> 27:08.027
I even had a little apron
made for him --

27:08.060 --> 27:10.429
had his name on it, too.

27:10.462 --> 27:13.733
Still, you know,
kids...

27:13.766 --> 27:16.035
grow up.

27:16.068 --> 27:20.039
I'm just grateful that he stayed
close to his mother.

27:20.072 --> 27:24.443
He could talk to her,
tell her anything.

27:24.476 --> 27:27.313
[ Voice breaking ]
So could I.

27:27.346 --> 27:29.749
And when she went...

27:29.782 --> 27:31.150
[ Sobs ]

27:35.021 --> 27:38.057
...I lost them both.

27:38.090 --> 27:40.126
Looks like he's back now.

27:40.159 --> 27:45.965
All I know is he ditched me
when I needed him.

27:45.998 --> 27:49.802
Well, you know,
as a wise person once said,

27:49.836 --> 27:53.973
"holding a grudge is a stone
in your heart."

27:54.006 --> 27:56.776
[ Sighs deeply ]

27:59.345 --> 28:00.346
What's that for?

28:00.379 --> 28:03.883
Local anaesthetic
for a bone-marrow aspiration.

28:03.916 --> 28:07.754
Why do I need
a bone-marrow aspiration?

28:07.787 --> 28:09.722
My attending saw
a low RBC count

28:09.756 --> 28:12.258
and wants
to find the cause --

28:12.291 --> 28:14.026
no biggie.

28:14.060 --> 28:15.261
"No biggie"?

28:15.294 --> 28:16.896
You're lying.

28:16.929 --> 28:18.965
What's going on?

28:18.998 --> 28:21.200
You already told me
I have terminal cancer,

28:21.233 --> 28:22.869
what's worse than that?

28:27.974 --> 28:29.241
You might not.

28:31.477 --> 28:33.145
It might not be
osteosarcoma --

28:33.179 --> 28:35.915
might be
Langerhans cell histiocytosis,

28:35.948 --> 28:37.784
which is treatable.

28:37.817 --> 28:38.818
Treatable?

28:38.851 --> 28:41.053
As in,
I might not die?

28:41.087 --> 28:42.521
That's why
I need to aspirate --

28:42.554 --> 28:43.923
to find out for sure.

28:43.956 --> 28:45.391
Do my parents know?

28:45.424 --> 28:49.395
Mm...I was told not
to get their hopes up.

28:49.428 --> 28:53.532
Then let's do it
before they get back.

28:53.565 --> 28:55.501
Roll onto your side.

28:55.534 --> 29:00.873
**

29:00.907 --> 29:06.145
**

29:06.178 --> 29:08.247
Is there a Scout badge
for aspirations?

29:08.280 --> 29:09.315
[ Chuckles ]

29:09.348 --> 29:10.983
I think someone
just made a joke.

29:14.854 --> 29:15.487
Hello.

29:15.521 --> 29:16.455
What are you doing?

29:16.488 --> 29:17.389
Painkiller.

29:17.423 --> 29:20.092
My arm hurts.

29:20.126 --> 29:20.993
That wouldn't explain

29:21.027 --> 29:23.362
why I'd be injecting
your lumbar region.

29:27.967 --> 29:29.468
Okay. Yes, hello.

29:29.501 --> 29:33.906
I think Evan may have been
misdiagnosed with cancer.

29:33.940 --> 29:37.009
I think he has something
that creates bone lesions

29:37.043 --> 29:38.377
that look like
osteosarcoma.

29:38.410 --> 29:40.379
It's a small chance, 0.3%,
but I --

29:40.412 --> 29:44.250
You -- You told Evan
that he has cancer?

29:44.283 --> 29:45.985
And now
you are telling him -- and us --

29:46.018 --> 29:46.718
that he doesn't?

29:46.752 --> 29:48.187
I'm telling you
he might not.

29:48.220 --> 29:50.189
That's why I need
to perform this aspiration.

29:50.222 --> 29:52.158
He says whatever I have
might be treatable.

29:52.191 --> 29:53.125
Are you insane?

29:53.159 --> 29:54.293
No. I am not insane.

29:54.326 --> 29:55.361
I thought you'd be happy.

29:55.394 --> 29:56.863
There is a significant link
between

29:56.896 --> 29:58.397
Langerhans cell histiocytosis
and --

29:58.430 --> 30:00.299
Go! Get out!

30:00.332 --> 30:02.234
[ Coughing ]

30:02.935 --> 30:04.403
Let me get you some water.

30:04.436 --> 30:06.205
[ Coughing continues ]

30:06.238 --> 30:09.608
[ Breathing sharply ]

30:09.641 --> 30:10.877
-Oh, my God!
-Hands right here --

30:10.910 --> 30:12.344
-[ Coughing ]
-Right here!

30:12.378 --> 30:13.279
Respiratory, stat!

30:17.049 --> 30:19.351
**

30:19.385 --> 30:21.220
He has a massive embolus,

30:21.253 --> 30:23.255
probably thrown
from his fracture.

30:23.289 --> 30:24.891
It's located
at the bifurcation

30:24.924 --> 30:26.325
of the pulmonary arteries.

30:26.358 --> 30:27.960
He's close
to hemodynamic collapse.

30:27.994 --> 30:29.161
Yeah, no kidding.

30:29.195 --> 30:30.863
I'd like to assist.

30:30.897 --> 30:32.098
Not a chance.

30:32.131 --> 30:35.101
Okay.
I'd like to assist.

30:35.134 --> 30:36.468
You're obviously
too close to the case.

30:36.502 --> 30:38.637
I think I'm just
the right amount of close.

30:38.670 --> 30:40.239
Murphy,
you lied to the parents

30:40.272 --> 30:42.141
just so you could try
to prove your ridiculous theory.

30:42.174 --> 30:45.945
You're too damn close.

30:45.978 --> 30:47.479
Saddle embolism,
scrub in.

30:47.513 --> 30:55.054
**

30:55.087 --> 30:56.889
Melendez: We have to get rid of
the embolus before he arrests.

30:56.923 --> 30:58.557
His heart
is barely pumping blood.

30:58.590 --> 31:00.259
I can feel
the pulmonary artery...

31:00.292 --> 31:02.528
I just need to find
the obstruction...there!

31:02.561 --> 31:03.429
I got it.

31:03.462 --> 31:05.031
Knife.

31:05.064 --> 31:06.398
EKG is showing
right heart strain.

31:06.432 --> 31:07.499
He can't take this
much longer.

31:07.533 --> 31:09.068
I know, but if I move
any quicker,

31:09.101 --> 31:10.502
I could nick
the left main artery

31:10.536 --> 31:11.570
and kill the boy.

31:11.603 --> 31:16.909
**

31:16.943 --> 31:19.278
The phrase "no biggie"
gave me away.

31:19.311 --> 31:21.413
You really got to learn
how to lie, Shaun.

31:23.449 --> 31:25.084
Am I in trouble?

31:25.117 --> 31:27.519
Yes.

31:27.553 --> 31:29.655
Unless you're right.

31:29.688 --> 31:31.557
If I'm wrong,
they shouldn't be upset.

31:31.590 --> 31:36.028
They know
it's highly unlikely.

31:36.062 --> 31:38.230
False hope, Shaun...

31:38.264 --> 31:40.199
it's just plain cruel.

31:40.232 --> 31:48.274
**

31:48.307 --> 31:56.315
**

31:56.348 --> 31:58.617
Hey.

31:58.650 --> 32:01.587
He talk to you?

32:01.620 --> 32:03.489
Did you talk to him?

32:03.522 --> 32:05.257
I don't know
what to tell him.

32:10.596 --> 32:12.264
You love your father,
don't you?

32:12.298 --> 32:13.632
Yeah, of course.

32:13.665 --> 32:16.035
Right. Well, he's about to go
in for brain surgery.

32:16.068 --> 32:18.104
There's huge risks involved.

32:18.137 --> 32:19.238
Whatever this lie is,

32:19.271 --> 32:20.306
can you live
the rest of your life

32:20.339 --> 32:22.008
knowing you kept it
from him?

32:34.520 --> 32:38.257
My -- My girlfriend
wasn't sick.

32:38.290 --> 32:40.359
Okay? She dumped me.

32:40.392 --> 32:41.660
She's married
with two kids --

32:41.693 --> 32:44.230
had no intention
of leaving them.

32:44.263 --> 32:45.264
I-I was an idiot.

32:45.297 --> 32:48.067
You got your heart broken,
that's the problem here?

32:48.100 --> 32:49.668
No -- no, Dad.

32:49.701 --> 32:50.669
The problem is...

32:50.702 --> 32:51.770
[ Sighs ]

32:51.803 --> 32:53.272
I didn't run away
to Thailand

32:53.305 --> 32:58.510
because I thought
Wilks' Grocery was beneath me.

32:58.544 --> 33:00.612
I was afraid
that I would never be able

33:00.646 --> 33:04.516
to fill your shoes...

33:04.550 --> 33:07.019
And then
I proved myself right.

33:07.053 --> 33:15.061
**

33:15.094 --> 33:23.135
**

33:23.169 --> 33:25.071
Left pulmonary artery's
open.

33:25.104 --> 33:26.205
Ring Forceps.

33:26.238 --> 33:32.644
**

33:32.678 --> 33:34.012
Come on.

33:36.648 --> 33:38.084
Got it.

33:39.518 --> 33:41.320
[ Exhales softly ]

33:41.353 --> 33:43.189
EKG is normalizing.

33:43.222 --> 33:44.190
He's okay.

33:44.223 --> 33:45.624
Nice job.

33:45.657 --> 33:47.559
All right,
flush the left pulmonary artery

33:47.593 --> 33:48.560
and close him up.

33:48.594 --> 33:49.595
Okay.

33:49.628 --> 33:55.834
**

33:55.867 --> 33:58.770
Um...Dr. Melendez...

33:58.804 --> 34:00.539
Take a look at this.

34:00.572 --> 34:07.179
**

34:07.213 --> 34:13.619
**

34:28.800 --> 34:33.172
Recycling --
Shaun, very responsible.

34:33.205 --> 34:35.407
It's a book.

34:35.441 --> 34:36.675
I appreciate that.

34:45.317 --> 34:46.485
[ Chuckles ]

34:46.518 --> 34:47.786
Thanks, Shaun.

34:49.688 --> 34:51.457
[ Door opens ]

34:59.398 --> 35:02.168
Melendez:
We got the embolism.

35:02.201 --> 35:05.804
He's in recovery
and he's doing fine.

35:05.837 --> 35:07.273
But while we were
in there,

35:07.306 --> 35:09.241
we did find
something else.

35:09.275 --> 35:11.109
Lesions on his ribs.

35:14.413 --> 35:17.549
Irrefutable proof
of osteosarcoma.

35:17.583 --> 35:19.785
It's metastasized
to his chest cavity.

35:22.388 --> 35:24.290
I'm sorry.

35:24.790 --> 35:28.360
[ Sighs ]

35:28.394 --> 35:30.229
[ Sniffles ]

35:30.262 --> 35:33.165
[ Sobbing ]

35:33.199 --> 35:34.833
I'm very sorry.

35:40.506 --> 35:47.813
**

35:47.846 --> 35:55.354
**

35:55.387 --> 35:59.725
Glassman: Give that
a nice, warm saline bath.

35:59.758 --> 36:02.728
Forceps and Taylor scissors,
please.

36:02.761 --> 36:03.795
Thank you.

36:03.829 --> 36:12.904
**

36:12.938 --> 36:14.306
Look at that.

36:14.340 --> 36:16.275
That's what built
the pyramids,

36:16.308 --> 36:19.211
painted the Mona Lisa,

36:19.245 --> 36:21.913
invented the Internet.

36:21.947 --> 36:23.415
[ Exhales sharply ]

36:23.449 --> 36:26.385
There is our interloper.

36:26.418 --> 36:28.487
Squeezeball please,
Deidre.

36:28.520 --> 36:29.588
Squeezeball?

36:29.621 --> 36:31.757
His name for it,
not ours.

36:31.790 --> 36:35.961
The saline gently displaces
the cyst

36:35.994 --> 36:38.397
and coaxes it out
of its little hiding place --

36:38.430 --> 36:43.635
Hopefully in one piece
so we don't have to call 911.

36:43.669 --> 36:45.704
Come on, now...

36:45.737 --> 36:47.973
Tray, please.

36:48.006 --> 36:49.641
There we go...

36:49.675 --> 36:52.311
A little bit more...

36:52.344 --> 36:54.346
And there we go.

36:54.380 --> 36:55.647
Got it.

36:55.681 --> 36:56.615
[ Exhales ]

36:56.648 --> 36:58.517
He has his father's eyes.

36:58.550 --> 37:00.286
That was incredible.

37:00.319 --> 37:02.321
One down,
three to go...

37:02.354 --> 37:08.460
**

37:08.494 --> 37:14.600
**

37:14.633 --> 37:17.002
Hey.
There he is.

37:17.035 --> 37:19.838
Hi, Sweetie.

37:19.871 --> 37:21.540
What's the matter?

37:21.573 --> 37:22.608
Nothing.

37:22.641 --> 37:25.944
We're just happy
you did so great.

37:27.746 --> 37:30.582
You had
what's called an embolism.

37:30.616 --> 37:32.884
It clogged an artery
in your lungs.

37:32.918 --> 37:35.487
But the good news
is they got it.

37:35.521 --> 37:38.357
And you're gonna be
just fine.

37:38.390 --> 37:39.458
Still...

37:39.491 --> 37:41.593
too bad
about the cancer, huh?

37:41.627 --> 37:42.728
No, no, no, no.

37:42.761 --> 37:44.730
The doctor did not know
what he was talking about --

37:44.763 --> 37:46.665
Dad, I know all about it.

37:46.698 --> 37:50.336
I have for a long time.

37:50.369 --> 37:52.304
[ Inhales deeply ]
I --

37:55.807 --> 37:58.477
I am so sorry.

37:58.510 --> 38:01.046
It's okay.

38:01.079 --> 38:03.349
[ Sniffling ]

38:03.382 --> 38:11.623
**

38:13.425 --> 38:16.562
Because I'm not
gonna be alone.

38:17.996 --> 38:21.400
Grandma's gonna be there,
too.

38:21.433 --> 38:25.036
Auntie Arlene.

38:25.070 --> 38:28.440
Uncle Jim, if he figured out
how to stop swearing.

38:28.474 --> 38:30.542
[ Chuckles ]

38:30.576 --> 38:32.744
[ Chuckles ]

38:32.778 --> 38:34.880
[ Clears throat ]

38:34.913 --> 38:36.582
I'll get you some water,
buddy.

38:36.615 --> 38:41.920
**

38:41.953 --> 38:47.493
**

38:47.526 --> 38:49.795
So, I took Penny
for a walk --

38:49.828 --> 38:51.397
just around the block.

38:53.699 --> 38:56.502
And I picked her up
some of those rawhide treats,

38:56.535 --> 38:59.638
you know...

38:59.671 --> 39:01.740
the ones that Mom
used to like to give to her.

39:08.046 --> 39:10.015
[ Voice breaking ]
I miss her, Dad.

39:10.048 --> 39:17.623
**

39:17.656 --> 39:24.996
**

39:25.030 --> 39:32.103
**

39:32.137 --> 39:39.478
**

39:39.511 --> 39:40.812
Evan: Coast is clear?

39:40.846 --> 39:47.052
**

39:47.085 --> 39:48.053
Yes.

39:48.086 --> 39:50.188
Thank you.

39:50.221 --> 39:51.890
Mm, I was wrong.

39:51.923 --> 39:53.058
You tried.

39:53.091 --> 39:54.593
I was wrong.

39:56.462 --> 39:57.829
Your parents hate me.

39:57.863 --> 39:58.830
I know.

39:58.864 --> 40:01.066
I gave you false hope.
Yeah.

40:01.099 --> 40:03.869
But for a minute there,
it was pretty awesome.

40:06.872 --> 40:08.907
I'm going to ask you
for a favor.

40:11.510 --> 40:14.212
Well, I'm not giving away
my Make-A-Wish.

40:14.245 --> 40:16.748
Mm, would you mind
if I read you something?

40:16.782 --> 40:18.650
It's not long.

40:18.684 --> 40:20.652
That I can do.

40:30.161 --> 40:32.731
"Atticus was right.

40:32.764 --> 40:35.200
One time he said
you never really know a man

40:35.233 --> 40:38.904
until you stand in his shoes
and walk around in them.

40:38.937 --> 40:41.707
Just standing
on the Radley porch was enough.

40:41.740 --> 40:43.041
The streetlights were fuzzy

40:43.074 --> 40:45.711
from the fine rain
that was falling"...

40:45.744 --> 40:49.114
**

40:49.147 --> 40:57.723
* I can't protect you
from the course of life *

40:57.756 --> 41:05.063
* But you know me
and you know I was born to try *

41:05.096 --> 41:12.604
* It's just the symptom
of a middle-aged attack *

41:12.638 --> 41:15.073
..."'Atticus,
he was real nice.'

41:15.106 --> 41:16.542
His hands
were under my chin,

41:16.575 --> 41:17.809
pulling up the cover,

41:17.843 --> 41:20.045
tucking it around me.

41:20.078 --> 41:23.515
'Most people are, Scout,
when you finally see them.'

41:23.549 --> 41:26.752
He turned out the light
and went into Jem's room.

41:26.785 --> 41:28.554
He would be there
all night,

41:28.587 --> 41:32.023
and he would be there when Jem
waked up in the morning."

41:32.057 --> 41:36.995
**

41:37.028 --> 41:39.565
Sounds like a good book.

41:39.598 --> 41:41.733
Could've used a spoiler alert,
though.

41:41.767 --> 41:49.040
**

41:49.074 --> 41:51.042
Thank you.

41:51.076 --> 41:55.146
* Confusing you,
from what you need *

41:55.180 --> 41:59.150
* Every hand that you hold

41:59.184 --> 42:00.852
* It comes back

42:00.886 --> 42:03.121
That's all.

42:03.154 --> 42:07.225
* Every word, every ride

42:07.258 --> 42:11.797
* It comes back every time

42:11.830 --> 42:15.200
**

42:15.233 --> 42:19.738
* It comes back every time

42:19.771 --> 42:24.876
**

42:24.910 --> 42:25.944
* Every time
